Which blob access storage tier would you use when dealing with a large amount of data that is actively used?
Hot


What Azure storage method allows you to take a “point-in-time” version of your blob storage account, and supports both managed and unmanaged disks?
ans is Snapshots
A blob snapshot is a read-only version of a blob that is captured at a point in time
Once a snapshot has been created, it can be read, copied, or deleted, but not modified
Snapshots provide a way to back up a blob as it appears at a moment in time
With the REST version 2015-07-08 and above,

Server-side encryption is done Azure storage service, and is enabled by default for all managed disks.
The encryption provides encryption at rest for your data
and is enabled by default for all managed disks, and whenever possible, snapshots, and images?

Regarding Microsoft Azure Storage, Table storage offers a NoSQL data store
Which type of storage within Azure Storage is optimized for random access files that are frequently updated?

You would use a Shared Access Signature to provide access to a client that can't be trusted with the account key.